"Where security and identity authentication are paramount, an identity assurance programme within the walls of government needs to be highly customised and capable of meeting a stringent check-list – durability, resilience, compliance, counterfeit resistant and tamper-proof. With the additional need for future-proofing, while still facilitating integration with legacy infrastructure, the security industry must continue to innovate on all fronts to deliver new programmes to specification, on time and on budget. Moreover, as employee culture shifts from workstations to phones and tablets, government agencies are not immune. All organisations need to find a means of accommodating all the different users in their operating environment, while simultaneously locking down resources in order to protect them from threats. Just as the lines of a distinct, defensible security perimeter are fading, so too are the lines between physical and online security. But the obligation of any organisation remains unchanged – to ensure its resources are secure. The adoption in the workplace of mobile devices has forced many to rethink the way in which access credentials are managed. A strong authentication solution that offers a means of issuing and managing credentials to provide different levels of security is critical. Ian Lowe of HID Identity Assurance explains how a converged physical and logical access control solution is an utmost necessity."
